                <head>No. 761<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On January 4, 1954, the Palestine Conciliation Commission submitted its
                    thirteenth progress report to the General Assembly, covering the period from
                    November 28, 1952 to December 31, 1953. The Commission stated that since the
                    General Assembly had not taken any new decisions with regard to its work, the
                    Commission considered that it was still guided by Resolution 512 (VI) adopted by
                    the General Assembly on January 26, 1952. The Commission stated that because it
                    had failed to obtain results by the procedures available to it, and because of
                    the unchanged attitude of the parties, it had for the present decided to
                    continue meeting at United <pb facs="1511" n="1471" xml:id="pg_1471"/> Nations
                    Headquarters in New York, where it would pursue its efforts to solve the
                    questions of compensation for the Palestine refugees and the release of Arab
                    refugee bank accounts in Israel. (U.N. doc. A/2629)</p>
            </div>
